WEBVTT

00:01.000 --> 00:08.000
♪

00:08.000 --> 00:09.792
JEN: I am telling you
there is a rat in the attic.

00:09.792 --> 00:12.333
I can hear it, it’s like
it’s on our old StairMaster.

00:12.333 --> 00:14.625
No, honey, we don’t
have rats, okay?

00:14.625 --> 00:17.250
Oscar, anything up there?

00:17.250 --> 00:18.375
OSCAR:
Rats.

00:18.375 --> 00:20.709
Oh, I told you we have rats!

00:20.709 --> 00:23.709
OSCAR:
No, no, I meant rats,

00:23.709 --> 00:26.750
I think I missed a very
important phone call.

00:26.750 --> 00:29.375
-Yeah.
-So, what is the,

00:29.375 --> 00:31.125
the sound up there?

00:31.125 --> 00:33.375
Oh, it’s probably rats.

00:33.375 --> 00:34.625
-Rats.
OSCAR: But don’t worry.

00:34.625 --> 00:36.375
If you got ’em, I’ll get ’em,

00:36.375 --> 00:38.792
adults and babies alike.

00:38.792 --> 00:41.667
Though, I mean,
these are just babies...

00:41.667 --> 00:45.875
Just babies, they ain’t
done nothin’ wrong yet.

00:45.875 --> 00:47.458
(crying)

00:47.458 --> 00:49.709
-I’m sorry.
-That’s--Yeah, do take,

00:49.709 --> 00:50.625
you take your time.

00:50.625 --> 00:54.000
I’m gonna compose myself
in your toilet.

00:54.000 --> 00:55.417
-No, no, that’s the baby’s room.
-Nope, wrong door.

00:55.417 --> 00:56.333
I’m sorry.

00:56.333 --> 00:57.291
(baby crying)

00:57.291 --> 00:58.291
It’s all right.

00:58.291 --> 00:59.375
Baby’s up.

00:59.375 --> 01:00.583
That’s okay.

01:00.583 --> 01:02.083
♪

01:02.083 --> 01:05.458
OSCAR: All right, I put some
traps all around the perimeter.

01:05.458 --> 01:06.959
Thanks, Oscar.

01:06.959 --> 01:08.875
I found this.

01:08.875 --> 01:10.917
Oh, thank you very much.

01:10.917 --> 01:12.875
I assumed it was yours.

01:12.875 --> 01:14.250
The reason why I have this,

01:14.250 --> 01:17.625
and Jen doesn’t know
about it, but I, uh,

01:17.625 --> 01:22.041
dated a girl
who posed in this issue.

01:22.041 --> 01:24.250
-Lordy be!
-Mm.

01:24.250 --> 01:25.959
She not gonna take a bath

01:25.959 --> 01:28.458
in that little
wood bucket, is she?

01:28.458 --> 01:30.000
She gone try.

01:30.000 --> 01:31.834
She even wrote me a little note.

01:31.834 --> 01:33.125
Oh, yeah.

01:33.125 --> 01:38.542
"To Greg, thanks for
dinner and dessert."

01:38.542 --> 01:40.959
Oh, I know what that means.

01:40.959 --> 01:42.125
(chuckling)

01:42.125 --> 01:44.792
Why don’t you put this
up on your mantle?

01:44.792 --> 01:46.792
Yeah, no, I don’t think
Jen would appreciate that,

01:46.792 --> 01:48.500
and she doesn’t know I have this

01:48.500 --> 01:50.792
-you know what I mean?
-Yup, I understand.

01:50.792 --> 01:53.542
Can’t imagine what you two
could be talking about.

01:53.542 --> 01:57.583
Oh, well, we’re just, uh,
talkin’ about, um...

01:57.583 --> 01:59.333
Dessert.

01:59.333 --> 02:01.208
-Dessert.
-And dinner.

02:01.208 --> 02:04.125
You guys, uh, you makin’
some dinner plans?

02:04.125 --> 02:05.625
Oh, that’s kind of ya,

02:05.625 --> 02:08.000
but my wife works most evenings,

02:08.000 --> 02:10.709
-so we can’t make it tonight.
-Oh...

02:10.709 --> 02:12.333
-rats!
-Yeah.

02:12.333 --> 02:14.375
(phone vibrating)

02:14.375 --> 02:15.542
Hm.

02:15.542 --> 02:16.959
I gotta go.

02:16.959 --> 02:20.250
I got a customer with
a possum in his chimney.

02:20.250 --> 02:21.959
-It’s not gonna kill itself!
-No.

02:21.959 --> 02:24.792
OSCAR: Although it will try
and fake it.

02:24.792 --> 02:27.208
Fool me once.

02:27.208 --> 02:30.917
Shame on you.

02:30.917 --> 02:32.375
I guess so, yeah.

02:32.375 --> 02:35.375
♪

02:35.375 --> 02:37.250
(yawning)

02:37.250 --> 02:40.542
-Thank you, honey.
-Uh-huh.

02:40.542 --> 02:43.500
(doorbell rings)

02:43.500 --> 02:45.125
Who could that be?

02:50.500 --> 02:51.959
-Oscar?
-I hope we’s not

02:51.959 --> 02:54.000
too late for dinner.

02:54.000 --> 02:56.709
-This here’s my wife, Tulip.
-Woo-woo!

02:56.709 --> 02:58.750
Oh, what a surprise,
I thought,

02:58.750 --> 03:00.667
I thought you said that
she had to work tonight?

03:00.667 --> 03:02.083
Oh, yeah, they sent me home.

03:02.083 --> 03:04.542
I have really bad pole rash.

03:04.542 --> 03:06.625
It’s very common
with dancers and firemen.

03:06.625 --> 03:08.625
JEN: Mm-hmm, yeah.
OSCAR: We brought you

03:08.625 --> 03:09.750
a bottle of rose.

03:09.750 --> 03:13.250
Wow, that’s so, uh, so kind.

03:13.250 --> 03:15.625
And, why don’t you,
why don’t you come in,

03:15.625 --> 03:18.709
and I was just in the middle of
covering all of our furniture

03:18.709 --> 03:23.166
-with towels.
TULIP: Oh, they have towels.

03:23.166 --> 03:26.208
TULIP:<i> So, Jen, Oscar tells me</i>
<i>that you were in </i>Playboy.

03:26.208 --> 03:27.875
(coughing)

03:27.875 --> 03:28.625
What’s that?

03:30.333 --> 03:32.417
Uh, no.

03:32.417 --> 03:35.333
No, I was never in Playboy.

03:35.333 --> 03:37.000
OSCAR:
Um, Tulip, my sweet flower,

03:37.000 --> 03:38.542
I wasn’t sayin’ that
his wife was in<i> Playboy,</i>

03:38.542 --> 03:40.417
I was sayin’ his girlyfriend
from college was in<i> Playboy,</i>

03:40.417 --> 03:42.625
and he didn’t want
her to know about it.

03:42.625 --> 03:43.834
-Uh-oh.
-Oh.

03:43.834 --> 03:45.625
Well...

03:45.625 --> 03:47.333
Honey, I never told you this

03:47.333 --> 03:48.625
because I didn’t
want things to get weird,

03:48.625 --> 03:52.417
but since that’s impossible now.

03:52.417 --> 03:55.875
When I was in college,
I slept with a woman

03:55.875 --> 03:58.125
who was in<i> Playboy.</i>

03:58.125 --> 04:02.041
Okay, like, you fell asleep
hugging the magazine?

04:02.041 --> 04:03.041
Ha.

04:03.041 --> 04:06.000
No, honey, we did it.

04:06.000 --> 04:08.166
Like, you know, it.

04:09.834 --> 04:10.959
Oh.

04:10.959 --> 04:12.000
Okay.

04:12.000 --> 04:14.667
Well, good job, Greg.

04:14.667 --> 04:16.709
Yeah, that’s awesome.

04:16.709 --> 04:17.750
All right, hey, listen.

04:17.750 --> 04:19.166
Is anyone gonna
eat this last Eggo?

04:19.166 --> 04:20.625
Oh, I was actually eyein’ it.

04:20.625 --> 04:23.709
Wait a minute,
you don’t believe me, do you?

04:23.709 --> 04:25.917
Wh--No, sure--No, sure I do!

04:25.917 --> 04:28.166
Yes, of course,
why wouldn’t I believe you

04:28.166 --> 04:30.667
that you slept with a...

04:30.667 --> 04:32.041
with a<i> Playboy </i>bunny?

04:32.041 --> 04:33.417
She gave me the magazine!

04:33.417 --> 04:35.291
Sweetie, she signed it for me,

04:35.291 --> 04:37.083
and Oscar saw it,
didn’t you, Oscar?

04:37.083 --> 04:39.875
I ain’t seen no<i> Playboy, </i>okay?

04:39.875 --> 04:41.375
What are you talkin’--
You gave it to--

04:41.375 --> 04:42.959
You found it,
and you gave it to me.

04:42.959 --> 04:44.208
I wasn’t lookin’ at no<i> Playboy,</i>

04:44.208 --> 04:46.333
certainly not
while I was workin’.

04:46.333 --> 04:48.333
Okay, come on, you know what,
that’s it, I’m gonna show you,

04:48.333 --> 04:49.834
all right, and for the record,

04:49.834 --> 04:52.125
I did not want this
to happen, okay?

04:52.125 --> 04:53.500
I’ve been tryin’
to avoid this!

04:53.500 --> 04:57.166
-So, honey, prepare yourself.
-Yeah, okay.

04:57.166 --> 05:02.458
Well, I will brace myself
with a glass of this rose.

05:02.458 --> 05:03.542
OSCAR: Mm-hmm.

05:05.041 --> 05:06.291
(gagging)

05:06.291 --> 05:08.500
♪

05:11.208 --> 05:13.625
It wa--It was right here!

05:13.625 --> 05:16.333
I put it right here, I swear!

05:16.333 --> 05:17.959
We should go.

05:17.959 --> 05:19.375
Tulip’s ovulatin’.

05:19.375 --> 05:21.125
I gotta go fill her up.

05:21.125 --> 05:22.125
Woo!

05:22.125 --> 05:23.875
Thanks so much for coming.

05:23.875 --> 05:26.166
I’m telling you it was there!

05:26.166 --> 05:28.166
Yeah, it’s upsetting, isn’t it?

05:28.166 --> 05:30.250
Knowing you’re telling the truth

05:30.250 --> 05:32.166
when your spouse
doesn’t believe you

05:32.166 --> 05:35.583
-because there’s just no proof.
-This is different, honey!

05:35.583 --> 05:37.041
This was real!

05:37.041 --> 05:38.500
So was the rat.

05:38.500 --> 05:40.583
There is no rat!

05:40.583 --> 05:42.917
-There is no Playmate.
-There was a Playmate.

05:42.917 --> 05:43.875
-No.
-Yeah, you wanna know

05:43.875 --> 05:45.417
how I know,
I touched the Playmate.

05:45.417 --> 05:46.458
-Really?
-Yeah,

05:46.458 --> 05:47.875
-in a lot of places.
-You know how I know?

05:47.875 --> 05:49.917
-How?
-’Cause I hear the rat.

05:49.917 --> 05:51.041
You don’t see the rat.

05:51.041 --> 05:52.125
-I hear it.
-Your hea--

05:52.125 --> 05:54.542
That’s a phantom rat
you’re hearing, sweetie.

05:54.542 --> 05:56.250
JEN:
Like your phantom magazine?

05:56.250 --> 05:59.542
♪

05:59.542 --> 06:02.375
All we want is
to build a gazeebo,

06:02.375 --> 06:05.333
but now the city’s telling us
that part of our land

06:05.333 --> 06:07.667
actually belongs
to the neighbors.

06:07.667 --> 06:09.291
JOHN: So, what
we wanna do now is

06:09.291 --> 06:12.291
sue the city
for being communist.

06:12.291 --> 06:14.166
Well, that’s a idea
that has legs.

06:14.166 --> 06:16.834
But let’s circle back to it,
and plan A, I think, is just

06:16.834 --> 06:19.333
asking your neighbors
to sign an easement.

06:21.208 --> 06:24.542
Unfortunately,
uh, Pam and Darryl

06:24.542 --> 06:26.333
don’t like us.

06:26.333 --> 06:30.166
We always seem to say the wrong
things at the wrong time.

06:30.166 --> 06:31.875
Okay, well, I mean,

06:31.875 --> 06:34.875
the amount of land
in question is only two feet,

06:34.875 --> 06:38.417
so I can’t imagine them
getting too upset over that.

06:38.417 --> 06:39.542
Two feet?

06:39.542 --> 06:40.625
What is that,
some kind of wise crack

06:40.625 --> 06:42.041
about my scuba diving accident?

06:42.041 --> 06:45.000
No, no, no, no,
no, not at all.

06:45.000 --> 06:48.041
We were just hoping to work this
out in a neighborly fashion,

06:48.041 --> 06:50.667
and I think we just got off
on the wrong foo--

06:50.667 --> 06:52.333
Seriously?

06:52.333 --> 06:54.625
-You can’t stop, can you?
-No, I can--

06:54.625 --> 06:56.709
You just don’t realize
how fraught with feet

06:56.709 --> 06:57.792
the language is.

06:57.792 --> 06:59.333
JOHN: Yeah, it kinda
makes it impossible

06:59.333 --> 07:03.250
not to put your foo--
your face in your mouth.

07:03.250 --> 07:05.000
Let me get us some more tea.

07:05.000 --> 07:07.208
Don’t try to wow us
with more tea.

07:07.208 --> 07:09.542
It’s nothin’ but a bag of dirt
in some hot water.

07:09.542 --> 07:11.750
JOHN: Yeah, this is pretty clear
this is not working.

07:11.750 --> 07:12.667
What is it gonna take

07:12.667 --> 07:14.250
-to get you to sign that?
-$5,000!

07:14.250 --> 07:15.417
Oh, my!

07:15.417 --> 07:17.834
-$5,001!
-No, that’s extortion.

07:17.834 --> 07:19.375
-$5,002!
JOAN: Oh!

07:19.375 --> 07:21.375
DARRYL: Keep on goin’, I went
to auctioneering school.

07:21.375 --> 07:22.333
I know how to talk fast.

07:22.333 --> 07:23.792
(vocalizing)

07:23.792 --> 07:24.750
Oh, nope!

07:24.750 --> 07:25.667
(DARRYL vocalizing)

07:25.667 --> 07:26.709
Sold!

07:26.709 --> 07:28.458
JOAN: Well, we’ll just
build the gazeebo

07:28.458 --> 07:30.667
on the other side of the pool.

07:30.667 --> 07:33.083
It won’t get the morning sun,
but you’ll still be able

07:33.083 --> 07:34.750
to sit on the glider
and whittle.

07:34.750 --> 07:36.750
Fine with me.

07:36.750 --> 07:39.709
-Aw!
DARRYL: Hello?

07:39.709 --> 07:41.542
PAM: Hey, ho, neighbors!

07:41.542 --> 07:43.625
We’re here for a soak!

07:43.625 --> 07:45.125
DARRYL: Turn up the heat
and make some room,

07:45.125 --> 07:48.125
-the McDougals are here!
-You’re getting in our hot tub?

07:48.125 --> 07:49.083
PAM: Yours?

07:49.083 --> 07:50.500
You mean ours.

07:50.500 --> 07:53.792
We are now co-owners
of this hot tizzy.

07:53.792 --> 07:55.583
DARRYL: Yeah, we got that
survey over to our lawyer,

07:55.583 --> 07:56.917
and he informed us that

07:56.917 --> 07:58.709
half this tub
is on our property!

07:58.709 --> 08:00.667
Oh, now wait a minute,
that can’t be.

08:00.667 --> 08:01.959
Oh, it be!

08:01.959 --> 08:05.792
♪

08:05.792 --> 08:07.291
What are we gonna do now?

08:07.291 --> 08:09.625
Same thing I did in ’Nam.

08:09.625 --> 08:11.750
Put on a coconut bra
and sing show tunes?

08:11.750 --> 08:13.750
Oh, I knew I shouldn’t have
shown you those pictures.

08:13.750 --> 08:16.208
No, we go on the attack!

08:16.208 --> 08:17.625
Oh!

08:17.625 --> 08:19.500
-Look at you!
-Oh, this gonna be so nice!

08:19.500 --> 08:20.959
-I can’t wait.
-You know it is!

08:20.959 --> 08:22.375
-Oh, oh, oh!
-What’s wrong, what’s wrong?

08:22.375 --> 08:24.458
-That’s freezin’!
JOHN: Whoops!

08:24.458 --> 08:26.750
Turns out the heater
is on our property,

08:26.750 --> 08:29.834
-and now it’s off.
-Oh, no, it’s on!

08:29.834 --> 08:31.750
And I’m not talkin’
about the heater.

08:31.750 --> 08:33.000
You done woke the dragon up!

08:33.000 --> 08:35.583
The dragon is up
and had her coffee!

08:35.583 --> 08:37.834
You about to get burnt,
neighbor.

08:37.834 --> 08:41.500
♪

08:41.500 --> 08:44.875
JOAN:
John, what’s in our hot tub?

08:49.709 --> 08:51.625
(groaning)

08:51.625 --> 08:53.542
Looks like cherry Jell-O.

08:53.542 --> 08:54.917
Actually,

08:54.917 --> 08:56.667
it’s Mixed Berry Blast.

08:56.667 --> 08:58.792
I accidentally spilled
20 packs in there,

08:58.792 --> 09:00.083
but don’t eat it.

09:00.083 --> 09:01.333
Pam made that mistake.

09:01.333 --> 09:03.792
Now that dragon’s got fire
comin’ out of both ends.

09:05.208 --> 09:08.667
Yeah, the security PIN code is

09:08.667 --> 09:10.583
8-7-1.

09:10.583 --> 09:13.125
Great, thanks.

09:13.125 --> 09:15.917
I just ordered 40 pizzas
to be delivered to their house

09:15.917 --> 09:18.166
that they don’t even want.

09:18.166 --> 09:21.291
John, you don’t
pay for the pizzas!

09:21.291 --> 09:23.291
That’s the whole prank.

09:23.291 --> 09:24.959
All you did was buy them

09:24.959 --> 09:28.458
the gift of 40 pizzas.

09:28.458 --> 09:31.375
You know, maybe it’s time
to stop this now.

09:31.375 --> 09:33.125
Yeah.

09:33.125 --> 09:37.000
(laughing)

09:37.000 --> 09:40.250
JOAN: Pam, Darryl.

09:40.250 --> 09:43.583
-You win!
-Yeah, we’ll give you $5,002,

09:43.583 --> 09:46.208
minus the $300 we paid
to get the Jell-O out.

09:46.208 --> 09:48.250
We’re way past deal makin’ now.

09:48.250 --> 09:49.834
You can’t put
a price on this!

09:49.834 --> 09:52.375
-Look at us, look at us!
-Excuse me?

09:52.375 --> 09:55.834
I come to find out that this
hot tub is good for my stump.

09:55.834 --> 09:57.583
I think my foot
is growin’ back.

09:57.583 --> 09:59.125
Somethin’s growin’
down there.

09:59.125 --> 10:00.667
(indistinct chatter)

10:00.667 --> 10:02.166
PAM:
Why don’t y’all get in?

10:02.166 --> 10:05.083
♪

10:05.083 --> 10:07.250
IN UNISON: Cheers!

10:07.250 --> 10:09.417
This is so much better
than a war.

10:09.417 --> 10:11.291
Oh, it’s so refreshing to,

10:11.291 --> 10:12.709
to have a clean slate.

10:12.709 --> 10:14.583
Yeah, nothing like sharing.

10:14.583 --> 10:15.875
Sharon?

10:15.875 --> 10:17.709
Why’d you have to go
and bring up that bitch?

10:17.709 --> 10:19.458
Look, I told you
that was over!

10:19.458 --> 10:21.917
She means nothing to me,
nothing!

10:21.917 --> 10:23.083
No, I said "sharing,"

10:23.083 --> 10:24.667
I don’t think you
heard me correctly.

10:24.667 --> 10:26.917
Are you makin’ fun of me
because I lost the hearing

10:26.917 --> 10:27.959
in my right ear?

10:27.959 --> 10:29.166
JOAN: Oh, no.

10:29.166 --> 10:31.542
It was a scuba divin’ accident.

10:31.542 --> 10:33.500
I went too deep
tryin’ to go find

10:33.500 --> 10:36.125
-Darryl’s foot!
-You didn’t go deep enough!

10:36.125 --> 10:38.500
Oh, well, maybe your
little precious Sharon

10:38.500 --> 10:40.583
could go find it next time!

10:40.583 --> 10:42.625
Sharon is a licensed
scuba diver!

10:42.625 --> 10:43.959
You are a snorkeler!

10:43.959 --> 10:46.625
-We’re just gonna go in now.
-We’re not goin’ anywhere!

10:46.625 --> 10:48.125
We are friends now, okay?

10:48.125 --> 10:49.959
Sharon, look.

10:49.959 --> 10:51.750
You just called me Sharon?

10:51.750 --> 10:53.750
Did you just call me Sharon?

10:53.750 --> 10:56.500
♪

10:56.500 --> 10:58.041
HEATHER:<i> Hey,</i>
<i>what did you just eat?</i>

10:58.041 --> 10:59.542
♪

10:59.542 --> 11:01.417
-Nothing.
-What are you eating?

11:03.875 --> 11:06.125
♪

11:06.125 --> 11:08.333
COLLEEN: Oh, I am so excited
for this dinner.

11:08.333 --> 11:10.208
JEN: Yeah, hey, how did
you two get reservations

11:10.208 --> 11:11.542
to Rolin and Jones anyway?

11:11.542 --> 11:13.041
GREG: I heard there was
a one-year wait.

11:13.041 --> 11:15.125
COLLEEN: No, no, it was easy,
the chef rear-ended us,

11:15.125 --> 11:16.750
-and we didn’t call the police.
MATT: You know, he said he’d

11:16.750 --> 11:17.917
just had a little bit
of cooking wine,

11:17.917 --> 11:20.291
but I could see some cooking
cocaine around his nose.

11:20.291 --> 11:23.375
HEATHER: Oh, hey, this isn’t
awkward for you guys, is it?

11:23.375 --> 11:24.375
Because it’s so soon
after your breakup?

11:24.375 --> 11:25.458
MATT: No!
COLLEEN: No!

11:25.458 --> 11:27.834
No, I mean, we were friends
before we were dating,

11:27.834 --> 11:29.250
so we thought,
we can do that again.

11:29.250 --> 11:30.333
MATT: Yeah!
COLLEEN: Yeah.

11:30.333 --> 11:31.583
GREG: Any of you noticed

11:31.583 --> 11:34.458
we haven’t moved
in five minutes?

11:34.458 --> 11:35.667
Must be an accident.

11:35.667 --> 11:37.875
TIM: You know, I’ll go check
it out, I gotta pee anyway.

11:42.333 --> 11:45.250
COLLEEN: How’s, uh, the garage?

11:45.250 --> 11:47.250
-Cozy, yeah warm.
-Warm.

11:47.250 --> 11:49.917
Hey, they’re not friends.

11:49.917 --> 11:51.333
What are you talkin’ about,
they’re fine.

11:51.333 --> 11:53.291
Exes, they can’t be friends.

11:53.291 --> 11:54.875
MATT:
Gettin’ a call?

11:54.875 --> 11:56.458
COLLEEN:
I’ll call back.

11:56.458 --> 11:57.750
MATT: No, it’s okay,
you can take it outside.

11:57.750 --> 11:59.250
I mean, none of
our business, right?

11:59.250 --> 12:00.333
COLLEEN:
No, it’s fine.

12:00.333 --> 12:03.667
-Okay, yeah.
COLLEEN: Yeah, it’s fine.

12:03.667 --> 12:04.583
JEN: Is it fine?

12:04.583 --> 12:11.000
♪

12:11.000 --> 12:13.750
All right, well, looks like
this is gonna take a while.

12:13.750 --> 12:15.208
They got a bunch
of streets blocked off

12:15.208 --> 12:17.750
because the President’s
havin’ a fundraiser in the area,

12:17.750 --> 12:19.709
and I guess the Secret Service

12:19.709 --> 12:23.125
apparently doesn’t
like hooker jokes anymore.

12:23.125 --> 12:30.500
♪

12:30.500 --> 12:31.750
MATT: Well, this is fun,
I’m having fun!

12:31.750 --> 12:34.000
COLLEEN:
Yeah, so, so fun, so fun.

12:34.000 --> 12:35.291
I am so hungry.

12:35.291 --> 12:38.125
Hey, I’ve got granola bars
in the emergency kit back there.

12:38.125 --> 12:40.834
MATT: Oh, yes.
JEN: Heather!

12:40.834 --> 12:43.667
COLLEEN: Get ’em out,
get ’em out.

12:43.667 --> 12:46.542
Huh, um.

12:46.542 --> 12:51.375
"I owe you
one granola bar, Tim."

12:51.375 --> 12:57.083
Uh, "I owe you
one granola bar, Tim."

12:57.083 --> 13:01.500
"I owe you a toilet paper, Tim."

13:01.500 --> 13:03.250
(cell phone buzzing)

13:03.250 --> 13:06.000
COLLEEN: Oh, you know what, uh,
I better take it this time.

13:10.000 --> 13:11.291
-Hello?
MATT: That’s weird.

13:11.291 --> 13:13.291
-Yeah?
-Here it comes.

13:13.291 --> 13:15.000
GREG: I’m just gonna pretend
to read this manual.

13:15.000 --> 13:17.709
MATT: It’s so private that
she has to take it outside?

13:17.709 --> 13:19.792
Right?

13:19.792 --> 13:22.125
I’m just sayin’ that’s
rude to you guys, hey?

13:22.125 --> 13:24.125
I mean, ’cause when you
get into a car with people,

13:24.125 --> 13:25.458
there’s a sort of
an unwritten contract

13:25.458 --> 13:27.166
that you’re gonna stay
in the car with the people,

13:27.166 --> 13:29.250
be loyal to the car
and the people,

13:29.250 --> 13:31.458
and not, like,
get out and walk away

13:31.458 --> 13:33.208
-from the car.
GREG: Oh, hey, uh,

13:33.208 --> 13:36.208
this car’s got its own
Wi-Fi hotspot!

13:36.208 --> 13:37.125
-Yeah!
TIM: You know what,

13:37.125 --> 13:38.625
I gotta whiz again.

13:38.625 --> 13:41.917
I got the bladder of an owl,
which I imagine is pretty small.

13:41.917 --> 13:43.709
Yeah, that’s true.

13:43.709 --> 13:46.333
Even elevator rides
are very difficult for him.

13:46.333 --> 13:51.500
♪

13:54.542 --> 13:56.208
MATT: Everything okay?
COLLEEN: Yeah, fine.

13:56.208 --> 13:58.375
-Good, that was just a friend?
COLLEEN: Really, Matt?

13:58.375 --> 13:59.667
You really need to know
who I was talking to?

13:59.667 --> 14:00.667
MATT:
No, I don’t.

14:00.667 --> 14:01.875
-No, it’s none of my business.
COLLEEN: Okay.

14:01.875 --> 14:03.458
MATT: I mean, is it rude...
COLLEEN: Nope.

14:03.458 --> 14:06.875
MATT: ...to get out of a car
and take a phone call, you know,

14:06.875 --> 14:08.500
when you’re hangin’ out with
your friend and his family?

14:08.500 --> 14:10.166
I don’t know, that’s
between you and the Lord.

14:10.166 --> 14:12.083
GREG: Hey, uh, Heather,
what is the,

14:12.083 --> 14:13.333
the Wi-Fi password here?

14:13.333 --> 14:16.250
I wanna watch some, uh,
waterslide fail videos.

14:16.250 --> 14:20.250
HEATHER: It’s, uh,
it’s hotforheater69.

14:20.250 --> 14:23.125
COLLEEN: Oh, I remember
low blood sugar Matt.

14:23.125 --> 14:24.959
-You remember this guy, do you?
-Yeah, real well.

14:24.959 --> 14:26.166
MATT: Is he anything like
your dad, ’cause if he is,

14:26.166 --> 14:27.125
you should probably
break up with him.

14:27.125 --> 14:28.041
See, that’s why
she broke up with me.

14:28.041 --> 14:29.375
COLLEEN: Oh, wow.
HEATHER: Hey, you guys,

14:29.375 --> 14:30.750
can I draw your
attention to this?

14:30.750 --> 14:32.583
Check out this map,
I can zoom all the way

14:32.583 --> 14:34.542
over to Hawaii, look!

14:34.542 --> 14:36.208
You know what, Matt, this is
not the time or the place

14:36.208 --> 14:37.291
-to get into this.
-Is it not?

14:37.291 --> 14:38.208
COLLEEN: No, it’s not.
MATT: No, is your little friend

14:38.208 --> 14:39.375
calling back?

14:39.375 --> 14:40.750
COLLEEN: Not my little friend.
MATT: No, but so--

14:40.750 --> 14:41.709
-So, it is a he...
COLLEEN: Mm-hmm.

14:41.709 --> 14:43.291
MATT: ...and he’s not little?
HEATHER: Hey!

14:43.291 --> 14:46.000
What did you just eat?

14:46.000 --> 14:47.834
-Nothing.
HEATHER: What are you eating?

14:47.834 --> 14:49.667
(yelling)

14:49.667 --> 14:52.625
GREG: I found one of Lark’s
teething biscuits in my jacket.

14:52.625 --> 14:53.542
JEN: What?

14:53.542 --> 14:55.083
That’s half mine, give me that!

14:55.083 --> 14:56.458
Spit it into my mouth
like a baby bird.

14:56.458 --> 14:58.083
You know what, I thought
that being friends with you

14:58.083 --> 14:59.083
would actually be
better than nothing,

14:59.083 --> 15:00.625
but news flash,
it isn’t, this sucks!

15:00.625 --> 15:02.667
COLLEEN: You think being friends
with you is a walk in the park?

15:02.667 --> 15:04.959
You are so passive
aggressive that sometimes

15:04.959 --> 15:05.875
I can’t tell if I’m talking

15:05.875 --> 15:08.166
-to you or your mother!
-No, you did not

15:08.166 --> 15:10.000
-just bring my mother into this?
COLLEEN: I said your mother--

15:10.000 --> 15:13.625
I did bring her up,
because she and you--

15:13.625 --> 15:14.667
(horn blaring)

15:14.667 --> 15:15.625
I feel like at some
points you are, like,

15:15.625 --> 15:16.750
talking at each other.

15:16.750 --> 15:17.709
You never listen!

15:17.709 --> 15:20.500
Ugh!

15:20.500 --> 15:23.333
Ugh, God!

15:23.333 --> 15:24.792
COLLEEN: This is, like,
the worst idea I’ve ever had

15:24.792 --> 15:26.208
in my life,
we could never be friends!

15:26.208 --> 15:28.458
GREG: So sad.
HEATHER: Oh, I know,

15:28.458 --> 15:30.458
they were so good together.

15:30.458 --> 15:35.458
GREG: No, I left half of
the teething biscuit in the car.

15:35.458 --> 15:36.959
MAN: Okay, here we go!

15:36.959 --> 15:38.333
JEN:
Wait, cars are moving.

15:38.333 --> 15:39.333
Cars are moving!

15:39.333 --> 15:40.709
-We’re moving!
-Oh, hey, maybe we can

15:40.709 --> 15:42.250
-still make our reservation.
-Yeah!

15:42.250 --> 15:43.792
HEATHER: Where’s Tim?

15:43.792 --> 15:44.917
GREG: Tim?
HEATHER: Tim?

15:44.917 --> 15:45.834
JEN: Tim?

15:45.834 --> 15:46.834
IN UNISON: Tim?

15:46.834 --> 15:50.500
♪

15:50.500 --> 15:51.542
Oh, ow!

15:51.542 --> 15:55.041
♪

15:55.041 --> 15:58.250
JOHN:<i> Oh, no, no, no,</i>
<i>I can’t lose my sense of smell.</i>

15:58.250 --> 16:00.291
That’s what separates
us from the animals.

16:02.500 --> 16:07.834
♪

16:07.834 --> 16:10.625
Well, I hope you can’t see
my memories up there,

16:10.625 --> 16:14.208
like what I said to Heather
the day before she married you.

16:15.834 --> 16:18.375
So, you, uh,
you have sinus polyps.

16:18.375 --> 16:19.458
Well, damn!

16:19.458 --> 16:21.125
I wanted to go out
on my own terms,

16:21.125 --> 16:22.625
-how long have I got?
-No, no, no, no

16:22.625 --> 16:24.917
it’s not serious, but you do
need to get ’em removed

16:24.917 --> 16:26.333
’cause if they get any bigger,

16:26.333 --> 16:27.500
you’ll never kick this cold,

16:27.500 --> 16:29.667
and you might lose
your sense of smell.

16:29.667 --> 16:32.917
Oh, no, no, no, I can’t
lose my sense of smell.

16:32.917 --> 16:35.709
That’s what separates
us from the animals.

16:35.709 --> 16:38.041
Well, I can refer you
to a good doctor

16:38.041 --> 16:39.834
-that can do the surgery.
-No, you’re doin’ it,

16:39.834 --> 16:41.417
and for free,
or nobody’s doin’ it.

16:41.417 --> 16:43.375
Plus, there isn’t
a doctor in the world

16:43.375 --> 16:46.291
who’d would be more terrified
of making a mistake than you.

16:48.166 --> 16:49.125
Fine.

16:49.125 --> 16:50.250
Great.

16:50.250 --> 16:52.583
Now, I’m gonna go
smell some things

16:52.583 --> 16:55.208
just in case something
goes wrong, huh?

16:55.208 --> 16:57.709
♪

16:57.709 --> 16:59.709
TIM:<i> This’ll just be</i>
<i>a really quick procedure.</i>

16:59.709 --> 17:01.291
You’ll be out for about an hour,
and when you wake up

17:01.291 --> 17:02.375
you’ll be good as new.

17:02.375 --> 17:04.625
-Okay.
-All right?

17:04.625 --> 17:08.000
Now just go ahead
and count backwards from ten.

17:08.000 --> 17:10.208
Ten...

17:10.208 --> 17:12.542
nine...

17:12.542 --> 17:14.166
eight...

17:16.583 --> 17:19.500
TIM:
Hey, do yourself a favor, guys,

17:19.500 --> 17:22.542
and Google "waterslide fails."

17:22.542 --> 17:25.000
Man, there are so many
bathing suit malfunctions.

17:25.000 --> 17:28.750
I mean, I was up till, like,
3:00 in the morning last night.

17:28.750 --> 17:30.417
-John?
MAN: He’s coding!

17:30.417 --> 17:32.583
John? Dad!

17:32.583 --> 17:33.333
Dad?

17:35.625 --> 17:37.959
♪

17:37.959 --> 17:39.917
How you feelin’, John?

17:39.917 --> 17:42.583
Oh, I feel great.

17:42.583 --> 17:44.291
You did good, Timmy.

17:44.291 --> 17:45.959
-Yeah.
-I knew you could do it.

17:45.959 --> 17:48.333
Oh, yeah, okay.

17:48.333 --> 17:49.542
I’ll see ya later.

17:49.542 --> 17:53.500
♪

17:53.500 --> 17:54.917
You’re my lawyer now.

17:54.917 --> 17:56.000
What, what are
you talking about?

17:56.000 --> 17:57.834
I killed John during
surgery this morning.

17:57.834 --> 17:59.458
He was dead for,
like, 15 seconds.

17:59.458 --> 18:01.000
It’s okay, we brought
him back, he’s fine.

18:01.000 --> 18:01.959
I mean, I think he’s fine.

18:01.959 --> 18:03.458
I don’t know what’s
going on in his brain.

18:03.458 --> 18:04.625
He might be oxygen-deprived.

18:04.625 --> 18:07.125
He might be some kind of
savant or something now.

18:07.125 --> 18:09.375
What do I know, I left before
the guy even had underwear on!

18:09.375 --> 18:11.625
Listen, I don’t wanna tell him
because he trusted me,

18:11.625 --> 18:13.375
and I don’t know what to do.

18:13.375 --> 18:15.583
CALLER:<i> Sounds like</i>
<i>I should call you back.</i>

18:15.583 --> 18:17.959
Yeah, that’d probably be best.

18:17.959 --> 18:19.208
TIM: Look, you’re
the only adult I know.

18:19.208 --> 18:20.709
Please tell me what to do.

18:20.709 --> 18:23.417
Well, ya just--
ya need to tell him.

18:23.417 --> 18:26.750
I mean, not legally,
but ethically.

18:26.750 --> 18:27.667
That’s it?

18:27.667 --> 18:29.291
Yeah, that’s what I’ve got.

18:29.291 --> 18:30.750
Well...

18:30.750 --> 18:33.250
Then, can I--I mean, that was

18:33.250 --> 18:35.208
pretty simple advice,
if I can--

18:39.875 --> 18:40.917
Time is money.

18:40.917 --> 18:42.333
JOHN: Okay.

18:43.917 --> 18:46.542
TIM: Okay, well,
everything looks great!

18:46.542 --> 18:49.375
The surgery was a success!

18:49.375 --> 18:50.625
Well, I knew
you could do it, Tim.

18:50.625 --> 18:52.291
You’re a good doctor

18:52.291 --> 18:54.291
and a good son-in-law,
thank you.

18:54.291 --> 18:55.458
TIM:
Yeah, um,

18:55.458 --> 18:58.500
there is one more thing
I wanted to tell you.

18:58.500 --> 18:59.667
Uh-huh.

19:02.375 --> 19:03.500
What’s this?

19:03.500 --> 19:06.000
TIM: This is your heartbeat
during the surgery,

19:06.000 --> 19:08.000
and this part right here is

19:08.000 --> 19:09.959
the thing that I
wanted to show you.

19:09.959 --> 19:12.250
-It’s, like, flat.
-Yeah, it is, yeah.

19:12.250 --> 19:15.375
It’s--for about 15 seconds here,
your heart kinda

19:15.375 --> 19:18.458
technically stopped beating.

19:18.458 --> 19:19.959
Are you saying I died?

19:19.959 --> 19:22.291
Yeah, but look,
we brought ya back!

19:22.291 --> 19:23.959
So, it’s all good.

19:23.959 --> 19:25.625
You let me die?

19:25.625 --> 19:27.500
-Um--
-You let me die?

19:27.500 --> 19:30.875
John...hey, remember,

19:30.875 --> 19:31.875
no charge!

19:31.875 --> 19:35.417
♪

19:35.417 --> 19:36.667
JOAN:<i> When did you see--</i>

19:36.667 --> 19:38.083
TIM: Well, I told him.

19:38.083 --> 19:39.542
He did not take it well.

19:39.542 --> 19:41.291
-Stop talking to me.
-All right.

19:41.291 --> 19:42.458
How ’bout now?

19:42.458 --> 19:44.834
I am a lawyer,
not a stripper.

19:44.834 --> 19:46.500
JOAN: Where have you been?

19:46.500 --> 19:49.041
We were worried.

19:49.041 --> 19:50.041
Is that a gun?

19:50.041 --> 19:52.959
Oh my God, he’s got a gun,
that’s a gun!

19:52.959 --> 19:54.333
What is that?

19:54.333 --> 19:57.125
JOHN: It’s my EKG from when
your husband killed me

19:57.125 --> 19:58.625
during my surgery.

19:58.625 --> 20:00.583
MATT: You let that man
operate on you?

20:00.583 --> 20:04.125
I would like to say that I am
just learning of this right now,

20:04.125 --> 20:06.834
and I am as shocked
as all of you.

20:06.834 --> 20:08.125
HEATHER:
Tim, is this true?

20:08.125 --> 20:12.125
Look, it’s not like we haven’t
all had this experience.

20:12.125 --> 20:14.583
MATT: Dying?
HEATHER: What?

20:14.583 --> 20:17.000
JOHN: No, no, no, no,
it’s okay.

20:17.000 --> 20:19.208
Don’t you see?

20:19.208 --> 20:20.875
I beat death.

20:20.875 --> 20:23.250
I think I might be invincible.

20:23.250 --> 20:25.875
JOAN: I don’t think it works
that way, dear.

20:25.875 --> 20:27.709
I’m so proud of you, Timmy.

20:27.709 --> 20:30.417
That was the most
manly thing you’ve ever done,

20:30.417 --> 20:31.792
killing a fella.

20:31.792 --> 20:33.333
That took courage.

20:33.333 --> 20:35.041
You did good, son.

20:35.041 --> 20:38.583
Thank you, that was
the plan all along.

20:38.583 --> 20:40.542
Pass me the chips,
and I’ll tell ya

20:40.542 --> 20:42.875
what I saw in the afterlife.

20:42.875 --> 20:46.083
Beautiful bright light,
a feeling of calm,

20:46.083 --> 20:48.583
and Jesus spoke to me

20:48.583 --> 20:50.083
about waterslides.

20:50.083 --> 20:57.000
♪

21:15.208 --> 21:18.000
♪
